  "updated": "2026-06-23",
  "_notes": [
    "Lexical lists are a FLOOR, not proof. Banned-word lists age: the PubMed study (arXiv 2406.07016) measured a ~25x jump in 'delves' in 2024 abstracts, and writers have since learned to avoid it. A hit raises suspicion; it never proves AI authorship, and a clean lexical pass never proves human authorship.",
    "Seeded from the PubMed excess-vocabulary study (arXiv 2406.07016: 280 excess style words, ~66% verbs, ~18% adjectives) plus curated practitioner lists. Edit freely; the linter reads only this file for word lists.",
    "Each lexical entry maps a tell to a suggested fix. null means 'usually cut the word entirely'. A value may also be an object {\"suggestion\": \"...\"} for forward-compatibility.",
    "Rotate stale tells over time: 'delve' spiked in 2024 then faded as writers learned to avoid it. Treat lexical hits as a floor and refresh this list as the model generation changes.",
    "The em-dash is treated as a strong tell, not a moderate one: em_dash_per_1k_words is low (1.5; AI uses the em-dash at 2-5x the human rate per Pangram Labs) and category_weights.em_dash is high (2.0). Replace nearly all em-dashes outside the creative register; creative already mutes em_dash + dash_style. The --fix autofixer rewrites em-dashes (and ASCII '--', spaced hyphens, non-numeric en-dashes) to commas and strips decorative emoji, except in creative (dashes + emoji kept) and casual (emoji kept).",
    "v0.4.0 retiered weights by what readers CITE as a tell, not what a scanner MATCHES (the ~90k-post Reddit study found these diverge). New Tier-A categories (sycophancy, aidiolect phrases, raised antithesis/bold_bullets) and structural checks (five_paragraph_shape, hypophora, superlative_creep, svo_monotony, name_selection, over_correction). Generic high-match/low-cited diction moved to soft_filler (weight 0.5) and transitions lowered to 0.5. See references/cited-vs-matched.md."
  ],
  "_filler_note": "Hard filler — distinctive AI diction that readers cite. Generic-but-human formal words that match often yet are rarely cited as a tell (comprehensive, robust, crucial, nuanced, utilize, navigate) live in soft_filler at a lower weight. See references/cited-vs-matched.md.",
